I got a (literally) last minute request from Prajwal. The bus station was closing and he was left without a place to stay after a long day of hiking the surrounding area. I only got to spend a few hours with him, but he came across as a really interesting fellow with a lot of traveling experience and good stories to tell. He's friendly, enthusiastic and in general a good ambassador for India. After meeting him and his praising of his home country I now have to rethink my next vacation :) He even made me an Indian breakfast before we parted. All in all a very good experience and I'm sorry we couldn't have spent more time together!

text: Andreas said he wanted to cycling around, so I called everywhere for him but couldn't get a renting bike, Shanghai is really not a bike-friendly place. We had to tour around on my bike and I was telling the history of Shanghai sitting on the back of my bike while Andreas was pedalling in front. text: My experience in Boston in Simo was fantastic! As I was in Boston for the Marathon, we met up earlier in the week to watch part of the Celtics game @ Faneuil Hall. On my second visit with Simo we had a photography night out @ a beautiful location overlooking the Boston Harbor and Skyline. After a few shots we headed back to his place where he cooked up great Moroccan Food. The Moroccan Chili Spices with Bread & Olive Oil and preserved Olives were soo good. If you dare to dive into Turkish culture in the middle of Hamburg with insider tips where to get the best food, if you want to spend time with an interesting host rather than just sleeping on a couch and if you and if you want to discover everyday something new, you maybe didn't know before or ever considered to think about - Utku is your man. Anastasia is a really nice host , she's always able to have good conversations despite of the topic, her place is very good located and she knows a lot of things about Hamburg , we really loved to stay with her. She's so kind and always able to give you the best hints , thanks for all :).

text: Anastasia was incredibly accommodating, friendly and straightforward. She was very easy to talk to and seemed happy to show me around. Also, the couch was just lovely. I was very grateful to be able to stay with her so last minute and had a really nice stay, I would be lucky to come back. ^-^

I stayed two days at Nastassjalz place, together with another couch surfer. She is a very nice, friendly and talkative girl, who you can discuss a lot of different topics with, even some special ones.
Since she lived for a long time in hamburg now, she really knows the best locations in the city to go to, which includes the best specific locations at the infamous Reeperbahn. Even though she had to work the next day on an early hour, she kind of gave us a tour around the place and we had some drinks at her favourite pubs and bars. She really knows where to get the best and cheapest drinks! If she hadn't had to work the next morning, I'm sure it would have been a long, funny night at the clubs :D

I definetely would stay with her again, it was a great time we had!

text:

And I have to say that one day is not enough time to visit Hamburg. I would definitively stay with them again! 

I am not good at writing references but I can tell you that you will have a good time in Hamburg, if you stay with Ann-Kathrin!

I almost missed out on visiting Hamburg  since I couldn't find a host. Tilman invited me and my cousin to come over and I'm glad we went. 

We cooked together, a mexican girl joined us as well. He took us to some beautiful places near the harbor. We also went to see the nightlife in Hamburg. Til likes to hang out, make fun and is considerate towards others. He is the kind of person that restores faith in humanity if needed. I love the way he lives with his housemates. I felt welcome, it was easygoing. 

Thank you, Til, you are a great host. Hope we'll meet again someday!

It was okay, not the best though. I AM KIDDING. 
If there was a prize for being the best CS Host, Tilman would definitely be nominated and probably win it too :) He's just so big hearted, genuine and thoughtful. The first night he organised a spontaneous bar-hopping with two other CS, we went to dance and we had fun all night long. Such a great evening! 

I also like the way he knows so many places in the city, he took me to places that I wouldn‚Äôt have stop over by myself and that were fabulous . (

If you have the chance, do meet this extraordinary man. He has so many talents and stories to share. 

Thanks you, thank you, thank you. Until we meet again T!

Tilman is a great guy! He accepted our last-minute request and we spent together New Year`s Eve. We appreciate it a lot!
His main rule was feeling like at home. And it was really enjoyable)

Tilman is an incredible host! Even if he had to build a new kitchen during our stay at his place, he made time to hang out and made our weekend in Hamburg the most memorable one. We just felt so welcome and are super happy with this first Couchsurfing experience. Thank you Tilman! :)

Tilman was an insanely kind host! We hitchhiked and he picked us up from a good location. He welcomed us with beer and a lot of energy. The house was clean, the roommates where kind and fun. Het took me into town and showed me some nice and hard to find places. In the morning we had awesome breakfast. We laughed, we had interesting conversations until 04:30 am. Still can't believe it :). Tnx Tilman, you were too awesome!!

Staying with Tilman and his roommates for the weekend was such a memorable experience. Going out with him was super fun , exploring the city in a tandem bike or taking a short walk to the lake was so awesome, getting to know his friends and roommates was such a luck and  sleeping in a tent in the cutess backyard ever make the whole weekend so special. Tilman its such a nice and caring guy and it's open to talk about any topic. Thanks for patiently listening to my "complicated"life and sharing your point of view!!!by the way you and your friends are very very welcome at my place whenever you like. Kind regards from Spain :)
Tilman has an awesome place and awesome housemates! He took us too some great spots in hamburg that we never would have found oursleves. He made us feel very home! Thankyou tilman!

text:
I had a wonderful time with Mirjam! She is kind, easygoing and funny. After 2 minutes talking with her, I knew I was going to have  a great time. We talked about all kinds of topics and shared our travelling experiences. 
I feel like she spoiled me: she cooked a great dinner, took me out for drinks and even went to the bakery to make me try the best "fake croissant" (I wish I could remember the real name ahahahah) in Hamburg! I am just sorry I didn't help her improving her French as I promised. Thanks again Mirjam!

My first meeting with Mirjam was marked with giggles. Then some wine and beer, followed by chats until past midnight like we're old friends. I loved how friendly she was and how excellent her music and literary taste was. Her home was the cosiest, coolest pad with music streaming at the best of times. She introduced me to German music which turned out to be so much better than the circulated 'German music reputation' that ever got to me (how ignorant I have been!). 

We cooked and walked and talked a lot. She facilitated my first German city biking experience ever. She sang and did little dances and hummed a lot, making it felt like home with a fun flatmate. I had the luck to meet her friends as well. They were excellent ambassadors of Hamburg, making me feel like it's one of the best cities of Germany. 

Goddamn, it's been gorge, Mir! It's not goodbye, rather an aufwiedersehen. I'll see you in some other part of the globe, ja!
I had a wonderful time with Miriam in Hamburg. Thank you for a great day! Hope to meet again ;)

inverseReference: {'id': '15953533', 'text': "My friend JP and I traveled through the US together, and when we finally arrived in Atlanta we had no place to stay. I am certain that if we hadnt met Taylor, we wouldn't have had such an amazing time in Atlanta. We wanted to experience Atlanta's local life and culture, and it was quite difficult, because it really is an insider-city and it's quite hard to find out where to go/what to see that is not touristy. text:
for my first time couchsurfing, i'm sure i could not have picked a better host. franzi took a whole weekend off from studying to spend it with me bikeriding around hamburg, joining me for a grimes concert and two exhibitions, sharing her insights on the city, delicious food and many long, intriguing and increasingly personal conversations.

i can't imagine a better way to experience a new place than the time we had together, and i'm so grateful that i was able to spend those two absolutely amazing, mindblowing and yes indeed, perfect, days with you. 

can't wait to meet you again. vienna, hamburg, or anywhere else - as long as it's soon!
inverseReference:
{'id': '10245323', 'text': 'This is quite a hard reference to write, because I feel like the days we spent together in Hamburg couldn't have been more perfect in the way they were! Starting with a long bike ride to the Elbe beach, eating ice cream, and enjoying the sun; we went to see Grimes in concert together in the evening. The next day, we started with an amazing breakfast and spent quite some time laying around on Antony Gormley's exhibition "Horizon Field Hamburg", talking about lives, loves and experiences. Afterwards, we saw another exhibition called "passage dangereux" by Louise Bourgeois who touched both of us extremely. Ending the day with another long Alster bikeride, good food, ice cream and a sundown at the Alsterufer sharing valuable thoughts.

One reason I love couchsurfing is that I get to meet people like you. I really wish you wouldn't live that far away, but who knows, maybe in the future you won't :)

I see you soon - either here or in Vienna! 
Until then - keep writing happy thoughts down!', 'createdDate': '2012-05-28T10:24:11Z', 'experience': 'positive', 'relationshipType': 'host', 'isPostTrip': False, 'to': {'id': '4274361'}, 'from': {'id': '532621', 'publicName': 'Franziska Boernicke', 'publicAddress': {'id': '3237769', 'description': 'Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany'}, 'avatarUrl': 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/ht-images.couchsurfing.com/u/532621/6532D2B1-FF43-4DDC-ACBD-AC0FE736745A', 'status': 'maybe', 'isVerified': True, 'isDeleted': False, 'blockedBy': None}, 'inverseReference': None, 'response': None}

text:
If I would have to describe my residence at Servets in one word, it would be simple..... Perfect!

Unfortunately I arrived 2 hours late in Hamburg, because my flight was delayed. But Servet was very flexible and changed his own time schedule to welcome me. After the very friendly welcome, he offered to show me around. 
After I have visited the places of interest, Hamburg offers, we went together to the local bar area (Schanzenviertel) and enjoyed some bottles of Astra (local beer). 

All in all, it can be said, that Servet was a very friendly host who helped me to see much of the "real" Hamburg. In addition he always respected my privacy. 
He is an open minded, smart and funny guy and I can just recommend everybody to take a stay at Servet's if you visit Hamburg!

Tom is a sportman , strong , funny and adventurous man.He is stayed two days with me and has discovered some parts of the Grande-Terre.We ve had good time in the lagoon of St Francois and at the Saline beach.We ve seen the interpretation table of Anse a la Gourde.Great area to understand the story of Guadeloupe.He needed to rest before to take his flight after a travel around Caribbean islands.We have had discussions about the life in general and it was interesting.Not easy to speak english all the time for me ! I wish him good luck for his next beginning in the active life and at work ! wish you a lot of anothers travel all around the world ! Thank you Tom !

text:
Ramin is an amazing human being. He is so cooooool!
Not only is he talented but he is smart, fun, wise and really nice. :)

We talked a lot and we got to know each other pretty well within a span of 3 days. He showed me around hamburg and talked about the history and important events behind the places. We also went to this really delicious turkish place just outside of Altona Station which I would recommend people to go to because it is soooooooo good, and share a couple of beers along the harbour. It was really nice to see how much he loved Hamburg and what made Hamburg different from the other cities. :) Ramin was pretty busy as well but I gave him space by spending the day by myself and we ended up cooking in the evening together.  He really gave me a unique and fun experience in Hamburg (so thankyou for that Ramin!) - you're in for a treat if you get Ramin as a host!

Ramin is one of the most genuine, intelligent, kind, generous, and informed people I've ever met. He embodies the Couchsurfing philosophy and makes this community light years better with his participation.

I was only supposed to stay 3 nights, but after hanging out over an amazing weekend, he offered to host me the whole week even though he was sick! But that didn't stop him from taking me to an art exhibition, a party in a WWII bunker, a Sankt Pauli soccer match, and the Reeperbahn Festival to name a few. We also had many lunches and dinners around Hamburg where we shared some really great conversation. He introduced me to several of his friends who were all just as welcoming and interesting as Ramin. I learned so much from him and was able to have legitimate cultural exchange through our interactions. We also had lots of good laughs.

Ramin, if it were possible to pick my siblings, I would choose you as my brother. Now come visit your family in California! :)

It was so nice to meet someone who is as open-minded as I am; being able to chat with him about anything and everything was really the cherry on top of a fun trip in Hamburg as well as my time in Germany in general. Patrick was very flexible about what I needed and always wanted to make sure I was comfortable as a guest. I fully recommend him as a host!

It was really uncomplicated to arrange things with him, as he was truly flexible. He is a smart, friendly, open-minded guy and you can talk about everything with him, even your opinions are different, which is a rare thing nowadays. We watched some football with him and a friend or had a drink and talk about stuff. He knows a lot about Hamburg or Germany in general, so if you are interested in that, just ask him.  He also has a great sense of humor, which some may find offensive, but not me.
The couch was in the living room. It's not that big, but I managed to sleep on it, so will you. He also respected when I was tired and wanted to sleep. 

The part I didn't like to be honest was the apartment. It was kinda dirty and dusty with stuff laying all over all the time. The shower wasn't really working and he didn't have a proper mirror, so it was kinda annoying to get ready in the morning.

BUT: this reference is for him as a person and not for the flat. If you are staying one night and/or don't need much to be comfortable, you`ll be fine. If you prefer a cleaner apartment and other surroundings, you should probably look for something else. 
Otherwise I would hang out with him any time again, he is a great guy and you can rely on him. Thanks again and I wish you all the best!

Along my journey, hitchhiking to Greece I made a few last minute requests, and in Hamburg to PS is one of them. 
Just before 11pm he wrote me back and said that, there was no problem me staying at his.
But it must has been some language barrier cause he thought I was coming the day after, so when I showed up around midnight he and his flatmates were confused at first, but of course they let me in. 
I had bought some beers that we popped and had good chat and laugh before we went to bed. They all left early in the morning but I had the chance to get a cup of tea " Indian style" .
They let me stay as long as I wanted, so before I hit the road again I spoke with their mate from chile. 

Even though I had a short experience of PS, I'll defiantly recommend other to surf or host him, he is very kind easy to talk to and makes you laugh.

Thanks again my friend, I hope I'll see you soon again.

text:
Annegret is a whirlwind of life and energy that picks you up and makes you want to dance in words and zest like good music on a summer night. I only stayed one night with Annegret, spending one all-too-short evening and disgustingly early morning with her and her boyfriend Flo. Our communication and plans up to finally meeting in person didn't run as smoothly as hoped, but all of that was blown from my mind once we met. If I had been in Rostock longer, I'm sure some kind of artistic (acting/music/illustration) collaboration would have emerged and Annegret would probably have mastered unicycling within a few days (simply because her dedication and enthusiasm for creating and learning is a force to be reckoned with). Apart from these sparkling superpowers, Annegret is also kind, understanding, interesting to talk to and, at times, simply ludicrously ridiculous in the best of ways (all of which - except perhaps for the ridiculousness - is also and equally true of Flo btw.). Simply looking through her bookshelves was a highly interesting experience in itself and having a fabulous vegan breakfast (unbelievably delicous homemade smoothies!) as well as a personal escort in Annegret, Flo and Spaceman Spiff all the way to the ferry this early in the morning was probably the best possible way to start the day!
Thanks a lot! All the best for the future and you're welcome to visit in Vienna any time ;)

text:
I met Manav in Paris through a hangout (first time the hangout actually really worked out - and yes it worked out to be simply perfect). We had a short but interesting conversation. Interesting enough to impulsively decide to visit him at his place when I was on my way back to Germany. Since Saarbrucken (no offence) is not well-known as The Typical German City (never even met a German from there), we joked that this would be perfect place for my smooth come back to the culture, language and traditions. What can I say, we had potatoes for dinner - so that‚Äôs a good start. But when it came to languages, I pretty much FAILED! (I would talk to the German people in English and to Manav in German in the exact same conversation - it was embarrassing). Luckily, Manav has a great, smart and outstanding sense of humor and culturally and stereotypically related jokes and puns are his Steckenpferd (how we would say it in German). I am glad I gave him a lot of material that he could make jokes about - great match, no? 

When my face muscles hurt too much from laughing, we were also able to have more serious conversations or would maybe say nothing at all and enjoy a beautiful hike to the Saarschleife with a beautiful view! Very neat. 

So, would I recommend him as a host? Oh yes, absolutely!!! And I understand... if you are not quite sure about a trip to Saarbrucken, the chance that you can meet up with Manav should help you making the decision. He is one of the main attractions from there (besides the huge and loaded blackberry bushes)... And, I know I made fun of Saarbrucken, but I admit it is pretty beautiful.    

Have space in your heart, Manav! Bis bald.

It was really interesting to stay with you and I would like to meet you again, maybe in my apt in Stuttgart. Thank you for letting me surf your couch!

Enjoy Manav's openminded personality, his cordiality and the wonderful view from his apartment!
